, compare it to the static case that has been studied in the prior literature.
 The seller problem becomes static when 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cor:tau=0"

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta M}{\delta\Lambda}=-\beta g'(y).\label{eq:dM/dW-static}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is concave, then full disclosure is optimal.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is convex, no disclosure is optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result easily follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "lem:main-lemma"

\end_inset

 using the fact that when 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(y)=(1+\tau\beta_{A}\alpha(y))^{-1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 When matching is dynamic, the original formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dM/dW-static"

\end_inset

 has to be adjusted for the dynamic effects, as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dM/dW"

\end_inset

.
 I now explain the additional dynamic effects in more detail.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make the contrast between the static and dynamic cases even starker,
 consider uniform distribution of seller types, 
\begin_inset Formula $G=U[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dM/dW"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta M}{\delta\Lambda}\propto-(\nu^{2}(y)-\nu(y))'\label{eq:dM/dL-uniform-G}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in dynamic setting and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\delta M}{\delta\Lambda}=0
\]

\end_inset

in the static setting.
 Therefore, the disclosure has no effect on the number of matches in the
 static case but does have effect in the dynamic case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two additional forces that appear in the dynamic case: 
\emph on
availability effect 
\emph default
and
\emph on
 patience effect
\emph default
.
 The availability effect arises because in equilibrium, high types are less
 available than low types.
 Therefore, the pdf of available seller types is decreasing.
 By 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:tau=0"

\end_inset

, this creates a motive for the intermediary to use finer disclosure policy.
 The availability effect is reflected by term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu^{2}(y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dM/dL-uniform-G"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The patience effect arises because sellers do not act myopically and reject
 low-value jobs due to dynamic optimization.
 High types have greater option value of rejecting a job (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "claim:option-value-effect"

\end_inset

), and so coarsening information has additional effect on acceptance by
 decreasing the sellers' option value of rejection.
 Note that this effect is dynamic and is distinct from the pure static effect
 of high types having higher acceptance rate.
 The patience effect is reflected by term 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nu(y)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:dM/dL-uniform-G"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

